# Catching PDO Exceptions

If you set error mode to `ERRMODE_EXCEPTION`, PDO throws `PDOException` on errors. You can catch them with try/catch.

```php
try {
    $pdo = new PDO(...);
    $pdo->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION);
    // queries
} catch (PDOException $e) {
    echo "Database error: " . $e->getMessage();
    // log error, show user-friendly message
}
```

```php
<?php
try {
    $pdo = new PDO($dsn, $user, $pass, [PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE => PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION]);
    $stmt = $pdo->prepare('SELECT * FROM non_existent_table');
    $stmt->execute();
} catch (PDOException $e) {
    echo 'Query failed: ' . $e->getMessage();
    // optionally rethrow or handle
}
?>
```

# Ensuring Data Consistency

A transaction groups multiple queries so they either all succeed or all fail (atomicity). Useful for operations like transferring money between accounts.

```php
$pdo->beginTransaction();
try {
    $pdo->exec('UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1');
    $pdo->exec('UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2');
    $pdo->commit(); // all good
} catch (Exception $e) {
    $pdo->rollBack(); // revert changes
    echo "Transaction failed: " . $e->getMessage();
}
```

`beginTransaction()` starts, `commit()` saves, `rollBack()` undoes.

```php
<?php
$pdo->beginTransaction();
try {
    $pdo->exec("INSERT INTO logs (message) VALUES ('Starting transfer')");
    $pdo->exec("UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 50 WHERE id = 1");
    // Simulate error if second update fails
    $pdo->exec("UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 50 WHERE id = 2");
    $pdo->commit();
    echo "Transfer complete.";
} catch (Exception $e) {
    $pdo->rollBack();
    echo "Transfer failed: " . $e->getMessage();
}
?>
```
